The story of Bruce Wayne's vengeance against the criminals of Gotham
might be exactly the kind of thing that the director of Citizen Kane
would want to make. Assuming Bob Kane and Bill Finger see Citizen Kane
and practically beg the auteur of the War of the Worlds to make Batman
his next picture, it might get made. Studios might not want to
confront such a project, but by that time Kane might be the type of
moneymaker that RKO would want to keep working, because he would make
them a lot of money, everything he touches turning to gold
figuratively. So if all goes according to plan, as the article states,
what would happen? Can we imagine the type of success for Orson
Welles' Batman that would be equal to Citizen Kane? Perhaps people
might see Wayne as another version of Kane. If enough interest is
there, then I do not see why it would not be regarded as successful.
</POST>
